# Git Commit Rules

## Format

`<type>(<scope>): <message>`

Examples:

- `feat(wf1): add order detail intent enrichment`
- `fix(repository): prevent duplicate message persistence`
- `refactor(adapters): simplify entelequia error mapping`
- `test(e2e): cover requiresAuth response contract`
- `docs(rules): add cursor rules for wf1 backend`

## Recommended types

- `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `perf`, `test`, `docs`, `chore`, `build`, `ci`

## Scope guidance

- `wf1`, `health`, `controllers`, `use-cases`, `ports`, `adapters`, `repository`, `security`, `sql`, `rules`

## Practical rules

- One logical change per commit.
- Keep subject line concrete and imperative.
- Avoid mixing unrelated functional changes in the same commit.
- **Never add co-author trailers** (`--trailer "Co-authored-by: ..."`). Commits should only have the author.

## Automatic enforcement

A git hook (`.git/hooks/prepare-commit-msg`) automatically removes any `Co-authored-by` trailers from commit messages to ensure compliance with this rule, even if Cursor IDE adds them automatically.
